title: Power Pod Insert for RV dash cubby

description.text:
Many RV's don't have a digital coach battery readout and those 3 light check panels are pretty worthless for monitoring the 12V supply state. I wanted a digital display that was always on and in easy view. Next the USB and lighter type plugs are on the passenger side of the dash and the GPS and brake control are of course driver side. Further, the existing outputs are always hot and I would like the option to shut devices down when parked without disconnecting their cable each time.

I found all 4 power modules in a plate for mounting titled: "12V Car Cigarette Lighter Socket + Dual USB Port Charger + Voltmeter Panel LED" on eBay.
The components were individually mounted to the plate so I pulled them and made a small insert pod to fit a cubby location in the dash.

description.text:
Revision 2017-07-30:
Insert stays the same. Renamed.
Outer made .50mm thicker. Renamed.
Holder made 4.50mm taller. (This makes all the bands the same thickness.) Renamed.
Old .STL files and some pictures removed.
I haven't yet made the new holder so the last 4 pictures are of the original design.

This is a reMake (not a remix) of the Hexy Coaster by daggius (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1643787).

I couldn't get his to load into my slicer ... so I designed one from scratch.

I added cutouts on the underside of the hex filler for drainage. I didn't want condensation to build up near an edge and overflow onto the table.

I also built a holder (instead of the suggested raised edge for stacking).

Swapping out filament on a single extruder machine isn't so bad ... once you learn the technique.

Printer:

Kodama Trinus

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.2 First Layer, .15 after that.

Infill:

Dosn't matter. I used 15%.

Notes:

I have a heated bed and tend to set it high, and keep my enclosure closed. Not really recommended for PLA, but I also use the BuildTak FlexPlate System, and removal from the bed is REALLY easy with it. Early prints of other items gave me lots of warped parts ... That's not a problem with my crazy settings.

The fun was when I discovered how easy it is to set pauses in my slicer. It pauses, I manually swap filament and push some through the extruder until the new color comes out clean, then continue until I repeat at the next pause.

I still use Pango as my slicer. To get it to pause multiple times, can add multiple values to the "Preferences / Expert Settings / Code / Height / Pause at Height" line. The entry I used was: 3.00 10.50 18.00 25.50 33.00 40.5.
I added some peel & stick felt to the bottoms of the coasters and the holder. You can get 9" x 12" sheets at your local craft store.

Notes:

I made 6 of the coasters and gave them to my son. He had guests this past weekend, and though everyone thought they were 'nifty' ... there were two suggestions for changes.

One is that the insert is too slick. You can probably fix that by using a flexible filament. I will, when and if I ever get my extruder to work with my PolyFlex.

The other is to make the outside taller than the insert. //While I will make some changes soon, you may be able to compensate in your slicer by scaling JUST the Z axis. Probably best to do that on the insert, especially if you use a flex filament.// See revision above.

Also, I thought it would be cool to stack them in an alternating pattern. The original holder didn't do that well, so I tweaked it and uploaded an "ALT" design. I haven't made one yet, but I'd love to see your "Make".

Thanks for the surprisingly high interest!

description.text:
Ever like the variable designs of FlatMinis, but the customization of Dungeon Dolls? Ever wanted more options? Look no further! Inspired by the aesthetic of GrumpyRobot's FlatMinis, and DutchMogul's Dungeon Doll system, come Trixster_98's take on the classic Dungeon Doll.

This handy Angel includes a double ended sword with an eye or without, pants with poleyns (Knee protection), rounded shirt with pauldrons, head with a halo, a base with wings, and a bottom of either 1x1 or 2x2 tiles. Try mixing with other characters for more types of winged beings. I printed mine at 150% which stands at 42 mm to the head, 47 mm to the top of the wings, and 70 mm wide wings. Fully customizable and modular, look for more designs to come in the following weeks.

These designs are fully compatible with DutchMogul's original Dungeon Dolls, but not with FlatMinis
Made in Tinkercad, printed on my Monoprice MP Select Mini

Printing
The pieces should be printed at 150-200% depending on what you feel your printers accuracy to be. My printer can make all the details clearly visible at 100% but needs the print to be at 150% in order to fit together well.
The picture shows the 3 sizes of 200%, 150%, and 100%

Preparation
In order for the pieces to properly fit together, you will need to lightly sand them with a set of needle files. The heads just need very minute sanding in the eye holes. My first layer is always slightly off which always needs work in that one spot. The studs that attach to the shirt and pants need light sanding, but the holes should be fine, depending on your printers accuracy. The shirt stud typically needs a very small amount of sanding compared to the pant studs. The bottom that fits onto the base will most likely need sanding on both the hole and stud depending on accuracy.

Always test fit pieces together as you sand. I'm not responsible for ruined pieces due to too much sanding.

Thought I would have a stab at a fume extractor for my first published design, idea came from working with my local maker space and how we could quickly and cheaply get extractor for soldering, so I took it upon myself to design something fairly simple and cheap to make.

The design is based around a 120mm PC fan with a 12v wall wart powering it through a switch. A bent metal coat hanger provides support where required however not necessary if you don't want to use that feature.

I printed all of the items in ABS, but this could easily be made in PLA well if required as there is no real stress or strain put on the parts and heat should never be an issue.

Design was done in Solidworks and I have included the original files as well as step files for each part so feel free to customise for switches and jacks etc.

Please let me know of any improvements or customisations you make I would love to see them! Also feel free to check out my weekly block on Wordpress www.thingbricator.wordpress.com

bed at 90 C

Sliced in Cura

Tools and Materials

To build this you will require the following tools and materials;

Tools

  • Screw driver
  • Pliers
  • Soldering Iron
  • Wire stripper/cutter
  • Needle files

Materials

  • One of each printed part
  • 120mm computer fan
  • Cooker hood filter
  • 12v wall wart
  • 12v dc jack
  • Rocker switch
  • 4 x fan screws
  • Solder
  • Super glue
Step 1 - Filing/finishing

You may get away with this but I presume not, I needed a little bit of filing after printing, the main culprit was the four fingers that attache the two parts of the filter casing together. I had to file all four to shape to get them to fit together nicely. I also had to slightly widen for my switch and 12 jack. Also due to the large overhang of the electrical compartment I had quite a bit of sagging which I had to cut out to install the switch.

Lugs after filing Step 2 - Fan and Filter Assembly

Once each part has been filed, check that the fan back and solder fan parts fit together cleanly. Take the fan frame and using the screws attach it to the fan so that the air will be sucked through the frame when fitted. This part has a counter bore to make sure that the screws engage into the fan and should stop you fitting it on the wrong way round.

Then carefully install the fan back onto this assembly using the four lugs, be careful not to snap them, I snapped one on either side of mine thanks to a weak print, however super glue fixed this.It just need to go together once and be fixed so glue is fine.

Finally cut a square of the filter material out that will fit the hole using a pair of scissors, I used a filter from a cooker hood that I found on eBay. Then install it into the enclosure.

Fan plate installed Step 3 - Electrics

Cut the connector off of the fan and identify the wires that provide power to the fan, mine were black and red, but they are not all colour coded like this. Easiest way to check is to look at the fan connector end on as it enters the socket on a motherboard, with the index mark at the top, ground will be the left most wire and the 12v+ will to the wire to the right of that. Once you have determined which are power and ground cut any additional wires back as far as possible as they are not required.

Cut the remaining power and ground wires to length, I cut them in half giving me some spare wire as well as a lot to work with. Solder the 12v+ to one side of the switch, solder the other bit of the same coloured wire which you just cut off to the other terminal. Feed the washer and nut of the jack over the ground wire and the power wire coming from the switch and pass them through the hole for the jack.

Solder on the jack, paying attention to your wall wart, it will show you if the centre pin is ground or 12v+. You may also want to install the plug of the wall wart into the jack when soldering, but do not plug it in just to keep the pin central when heat is applied.

Install the jack and tighten up the nut holding it in place. test that the fan and switch work and adjust if required. Finally slide the enclosure onto the bottom of the ban until the holes line up.

Step 4 - Wire Support

The two holes on the bottom are for a metal cable tie to be inserted to make a support arrangement, this is optional as the fan works as it currently is.

TO make the support get a metal coat hanger and straighten it out best you can, cutting overly bent bits like the hook out if required. Using a pair of pliers and a tape measure bend a stand which is roughly 95mm wide and at least 30mm high, the support arms that are inserted into the fan need to be minimum 50mm long.

Once finished insert them into the holes, they may need fettling with a file as I found some coat hangers thicker than others.

Bending the legs Final product

description.text:
I designed this for those who have ClosetMaid shelving (the rack looking ones) near or above their printer like I do. I actually built a full shelf in my double door closet just below chest high and I have both my 3d printers and an old laptop (running Octoprint on Linux). At the top there is a ClosetMaid brand shelf but it sits just a little to high to place filament on top. I needed a way to hang them...all of them (variety of sizes). I found a few people have already designed spoolholders for the closet maid like BuddyC (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:617540) but I wanted mine recessed more to give me more room. I designed mine to snap into the corner of the shelf like the cloths pole does. but since the weight is in the back, I reverse the clips in the front. This allows full strength and easier removal. Also I made it so that the spool can be removed without having to remove the entire mounts. It supports up to a 5/16 rod/dowel.

The label frame comes in two versions:

  • one with a filament guide
  • one without a filament guide

I've also included a universal spool wheel; but found there are better ones out there like:

  • https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1241566

Overview

Here's a police car toothbrush holder design, in case anyone else has a 4 year old with a similar set of likes as mine.

Design Tools

I moulded the chassis in Blender and added the wheel wells, wheels, and insets for toothbrushes in TinkerCAD.

Versions

The first version (see picture of actual print) was too small to hold my son's toothbrush and I worried that even had the hole been large enough, it wouldn't have worked because the cylinder isn't deep enough. The second version corrects for this at the cost of aesthetics. Form follows function, I suppose.

The sizing issue on V1 came because of the size of the build plate on the Monoprice Select Mini, so there was really nothing to be done about it, unfortunately.

Print completed

The second version was printed in red ABS on a FlashForge Creator Pro. I printed on the FlashForge slicer's Fast Print default settings.

It took quite some time but I finally finished my AT-ST Scout Walker from Star Wars tonight!
It was quite hard to not make a million parts but to keep it printable. I hope I succeeded in doing so but I didn't have time to print my own one (yet :-)) Base model credits to Sketchup user Guinlann.
Thanks for the designers of the Dreadnought and Yoda. They gave me the inspiration to draw this one.
Hope you like it!
EDIT 23-3-2013: Sven Grundmann repaired the STL's! They appear to be printable now.

Start by downloading the files. There's a ZIP including all the STL's you'll need. There's also a Sketchup model available so you can make adjustment to the design if you like. The AT-ST Walker consists of 19 parts (18 STLs available, Kneepad goes twice). Some of them are unique but many of them are mirrored versions. 1x Body part
2x Head back detail left (1x right, 1x left)
1x Head main part
1x Head mouth gun part
1x Head top part
2x Kneepad
1x Left ear gun
1x Left ear
2x Leg foot (1x right, 1x left)
2x Leg thigh (1x right, 1x left)
2x Leg hip (1x right, 1x left)
1x Neck piece
1x Right ear gun
1x Right ear Print all the parts. In some of the parts there are alignment holes. The diameter of these holes should be 3.2mm so you can insert a smal piece of filament to align and connect (by glueing) the parts together. I've drawn this thing in a combination of PTC Creo (for the more complex bits) and mostly Sketchup. I had some problem getting all the parts manifold. Some help would be appreciated there. I repaired the parts as best as I could with Meshlab and Netfabb.
Since the STL's gave a lot of problems printing still no one was able to 3D print this object. Luckily Sven Grundmann from Germany came in and saved this object from the digital cemetry and brought it to life. He repaired the STL files and send them to me by mail to share them with you! All credits go to Sven! I HIGHLY RECOMMEND PRINTING THE PARTS AND CHECK IF IT FITS! Last but not least: Have fun printing and enjoy the AT-ST Scout Walker! EDIT 9-7-2012: OBJ files addes to the list
EDIT 23-3-2013: Deleted my own files and added Sven Grundmann's files (with his permission)

title: Steam knob for Rancilio Nancy espresso machine

description.text:
The steam knob on my ancient Rancilio Nancy espresso machine stripped and I couldn't buy a replacement, so I printed one. Pictures: http://imgur.com/a/n7trc

Unlike the original factory design which used a clip to attach the knob & shaft to the steam valve, this design simply fits completely over the D-slot on the steam valve. Accordingly, you may need to slide the clip off the D-slot if it's still attached - you can probably do this without opening up the machine by using a pair of needlenose pliers through the hole where the knob goes.

The design fits snugly over the D-slot on the valve in my machine, but if you have issues with fit, I've included the original .SLDPRT file if you want to make adjustments.

description.text:
With the new 2S tinyPEPPER 4 in 1 ESC being released i was able to slim down the CF Stick quad a bit. With a 2S airbladeuav 450mah battery AUW is just over 61g.

The picture shows it assembled but a bit tall, i need shorter standoffs or spacers to squish the stack, and the VTX antenna is way too long.

This rebuild of the CF Stick Quad also has a different camera/vtx. The VTX is an Eachine VTX03 running on a pololu 5v regulator paired with a generic 600tvl cmos camera i had on the bench angled at 30 degrees.

Check out the flight video

Update Sept 14th 2017:

I edited the motor mounts so they're take the 1103's which have both the 8.5mm and 9mm bolt pattern. I also strengthened the camera mount after completely destroying the original in a crash.

Notes:

After it broke apart during testing, I've found PETG isn't durable enough for the main plate, but seems fine for the motor mounts. You'll either want to use nylon or thicken this design a good bit.

I printed this with no supports, so there was a bit of sagging to clean up from the first layer of bridging. I used a hobby knife to clear anything obviously in the way.

Then I filed each CF Stick hole with a small square file until the CF just barely fit.

I'm using 3mm square CF with a 1.5mm center hole, it was available at my local hobby shop in about meter long pieces. Each stick is cut to 100mm and centered properly before gluing.

After centering the CF sticks i glued them in place with a bit of CA glue dead center where the sticks overlap and a drop in the open hole of each of the motor mounts. Previously i was drilling the CF and bolting it into the plastic with 1.6mm screws. That was very secure but introduced weaknesses in the CF where it would snap more easily in a bad crash.

Inside to tape rolls for better using on plotter. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z6GaBOqir8Q

Portable "Connect Four" game complete with coins.

The game includes a board, two different coin styles, two caps and a font logo. The two caps are used to make the game portable and ensure that no coins are lost during transport. The two caps are also used to give a stable stand while playing (see picture).

There are two coin styles included (style A and B). Use whatever fits your taste. You'll need at least 21 coins per player. Use the "x25" files to print 25 coins at once. I also included .stl files with single coins in case you lost one and need to print a single coin only.

Printing the included font logo is optional. It's not mandatory but gives a decent look to your game. Use some glue to stick the logo on the board.

Can be printed in various sizes:

100% - 'Indoor' size (appropriate for kids and seniors)
75% - Portable size (for outdoor and travelling)

Printing:

  • Print all files in the orientation as provided in the .stl files.

  • No supports are needed, but make sure your heatbed has a good adhesion. Use a brim and heatbed temp of 60-65 degrees for best adhesion.

  • All files can be printed with a layer height of 0.3mm (less printing time). But you may also use 0.2mm of course.

  • Use Cura if Simplify3D refuses to import meshes correctly. Cura has better mesh importing capabilities.
